review_text:
I selected this book from the library simply because it was one of the few books that were readily available. Being a Murakami book, I thought that it would definitely be a nice read and so I borrowed it. Little did I know that this small book packed a punch within its covers, whose pages were bursting with some wonderful philosophies and some really interesting insights into Murakami’s mind and thought process.What I talk about when I talk about running – The title itself is interesting and pleads with you to ask that question of yourself, even if you aren’t a habitual runner. Okay confession time – I don’t run, not that I hate running or anything but that I am one lazy person, a couch potato who likes her books more than anything. And despite that, I put this question to myself, or rather worded it differently and said what I talk about when I talk about doing something mechanical. Runners in this forum do not take up your sword against me, I am not calling running a mechanical activity but am simply saying that doing something mechanical is the only thing I do differently from reading, and you have to accept that reading is not a mechanical chore but a pleasant ride into the infinity. Anyway, coming back to the question that I had put to myself, the only answer that was possible was that – I thought of NOTHING, no thoughts, zilch!! It was as if my mind decides to take a break and disappear when I do something mechanical so that there is a void or rather a semblance of a void. Intrigued by my own reaction, I decided to see whether Murakami agreed or disagreed with me and I am really happy to say that he did agree, in a fashion! Oh don’t worry that is not a spoiler, in fact this is one book that I can review happily without ever giving any spoilers for the review will mostly be subjective, being my interpretation, which as you know will differ for different people. Coming back to the book, Murakami adopts a very different style for this one, given that it is part autobiographical, being a memoir of sorts where he links his running and writing and how the two do meet at times and yet differ at times. This book is inspiring, full of quotes that make you nod your head and say that yes I have experienced that or I know what that feels like or that I can empathise because I have seen it happen to others. Whatever your scenario, Murakami writes to the reader and the reader, at least this reader, connected to it really well and we became thick friends in this small passage of time. Here's a sample;

“Don’t misunderstand me – I’m not totally uncompetitive. It’s just that for some reason I never care all that much whether I beat others or lost to them. This sentiment pretty much remained unchanged after I grew up. It doesn’t matter what field you are talking about – beating somebody else just doesn’t do it for me. I’m much more interested in whether I reach the goals that I set for myself…”

His prose is self-deprecating, funny and motivating, whilst also resonating some anguish, not at failing but at being unable to find the reason for that failure. I loved it for different reasons, one being that it spoke to me;

“Life is basically unfair. But even in a situation that’s unfair, I think it’s possible to seek out a kind of fairness. Of course, that might take time and effort. And maybe it won’t seem to be worth all that. It’s up to each individual to decide whether or not it is.”

There is all this and more in this book but the beauty lies not in its inspiring message but in the fact that Murakami does not preach at any point in this book. All the statements made by him or epiphanies that occurred to him are all just jotted down as mere observations. In the beginning of the book, he clearly says that this is not a book to motivate others to take up long distance running but if someone chooses to do so and finds it enjoyable then it is like a cherry on an existing cake.I found this short book interesting and I have to say that inspired me to stop being a couch potato. Of course, like Murakami says, unless that change comes from within, it won’t last. Whether I will continue in my effort to staying fit is a topic for another day, today however, I feel that Murakami definitely ruled the roost with this small yet captivating book. Do read it, if you can, it isn’t great literature but it is definitely something that all of us will relate to in some way or the other!
